title.label: I want to give five stars.

content.label:
It‚Äôs my most-played mobile game, and I love it. 

But it gave me the impression that by tipping the developer a dollar (through the in-game ‚Äústore‚Äù) that I could remove ads. 

Not so. 

It appears you actually have to exchange money for in-game currency to disable ads. 

Here‚Äôs the swindle: 

When you go into the options menu and tap ‚Äúads: enabled,‚Äù the game tells you that you can buy ‚Äúany of PUNCH QUEST‚ÄôS in-app purchases‚Äù to disable ads. 

The game then invites you to tap thru to the store. The cheapest of the items available there is a $0.99 ‚Äútip‚Äù for the developers ‚Äîwith the flavor text, ‚ÄúLike the game but don‚Äôt want to buy coins? Tip us a dollar instead!‚Äù

Now of course, they distinguished this ‚Äútip‚Äù from a ‚Äúpurchase,‚Äù and if I had been a more careful buyer, I might have hesitated to classify the $0.99 option as one of ‚ÄúPUNCH QUEST‚ÄôS in-app purchases.‚Äù

Then again, the ‚Äútip‚Äù was in the store to which the drill-down in the options menu led me. Why include it there if it‚Äôs not one of ‚ÄúPUNCH QUEST‚ÄôS in-app purchases?‚Äù

The amount of money involved is trivial, but I‚Äôm leaving the one star to reflect the sting of disappointment I felt when an otherwise open and honest game that I love (and in which micro transactions and ads aren‚Äôt disruptive in any meaningful way) hustled me.

If it‚Äôs ‚Äúcaveat emptor,‚Äù then I say let the developer beware of slick sales tactics before shopping for five stars at my boutique. 

TL;DR, paid a dollar, still can‚Äôt turn ads off. Leaving the one star until I get my dollar back. Will make a different purchase in the in-app store upon refund of the ‚Äútip‚Äù I left.
